dataset.title: Estimates of walleye abundance for Oneida Lake, NY (1957-2008)

abstract.para: The Cornell Biological Field Station (CBFS) serves as a primary field site for aquatic research at Cornell University (more information can be found at http://www.cbfs.dnr.cornell.edu) and is part of the Department of Natural Resources, College of Agriculture and Life Sciences at Cornell University. The centerpiece of the station's research program is a 50-year database on the food web of Oneida Lake, New York, that has been collected with support from the Cornell University Brown Endowment and from the New York State Department of Environmental Conservation. The data are collected by personnel from the Cornell Biological Field Station and include limnology, benthos, zooplankton, phytoplankton, and fish survey data, primarily from Oneida Lake and spanning 1957 to the present. This dataset reports the CBFS estimates of walleye abundance at different stage and age groups in Oneida Lake. These estimates are based on data from standard trawl (1961-2008; http://hdl.handle.net/1813/11217) and gill net catches (1959-2008; http://hdl.handle.net/1813/11216), mark-recapture estimates for age 4 and older walleye, an analysis combining these data sets (Irwin et al. 2008), Miller sampler surveys for larval walleye, and information from the Constantia Fish Cultural Station on number of newly hatched larval walleye stocked each year. There are two primary data tables: one with the estimated abundance in # fish/ha for age 1 and older walleye in April of each year, and one with estimated abundance, length, and sampling dates for age-0 walleye (larvae, juveniles, age-1 in the following spring). An additional table, catchability, contains numbers used to estimate walleye abundance as described in the methods section.

section.title: Stocking information
section.para: Number of walleye stocked by the Oneida Fish Cultural Station (OFCS) at Constantia, operated by New York Department of Environmental Conservation. Walleye larvae are stocked soon after hatching at the OFCS. The numbers stocked are provided by OFCS fish hatchery managers (most recently Richard Colesante up to 2000, Mark Babenzien since 2000). Since 1977, the number of larvae is calculated by volume displacement and is quantitative. Up to 1976, the number of larvae was estimated from measured number of eggs and an estimated hatching success of 82% (by eye). These may be overestimates as measured hatching success from egg to larvae in 1977-1985 was 52%. No correction was applied as estimation of hatching success by previous hatchery managers is unknown. Numbers stocked noted as 102 million (1982 to 1991) are likely underestimates as this 102 million represent the quota for Oneida Lake, and more larvae were typically stocked (possibly 20% more). Stocking dates refer to dates that Oneida Lake was stocked.

section.title: Larval walleye surveys
section.para: Miller high-speed sampler surveys are designed to estimate abundance of larval walleye and yellow perch. Larval walleye have been sampled approximately 9 days after stocking by the Constantia Fish Cultural Station and when yellow perch reach approximately 8 mm. For each survey, the lake is divided into two or more horizontal and vertical depth strata and samples taken at approximately 50 randomly selected sites within designated strata. At each site, four Miller samplers are towed simultaneously at different depths and catches are pooled by stratum. Distance towed is about 1.6 km at a speed of 3.6 m/s. Larval fish captured are identified, counted, and measured. Density is based on catches between 0 and 6 m depth, as few fish were caught deeper when deeper tows were made. Deeper tows are not available for all years.

section.title: Otter trawl surveys
section.para: The standard 5.9 m otter trawl used on Oneida Lake was modeled after a 4 seam shrimp trawl. The trawl consisted of a 5.9 m footrope, a 38 mm stretch mesh body, and 13 mm cod end (Forney, 1976), and measured 5.5 m across under tow. The net was attached to flat boards (with an area of 0.32 m2) with double 1 m bridles. Trawl ropes (9.5 mm diameter) were 48 m long, and were marked 26 m from the trawl board (for the 4 shallow sites) and 38 m from the board (for the 6 deep sites). Hauls were conducted for 5 minutes at a speed of 3.4 km/h, sampling an area of approximately 1,000 m2. Weekly hauls were conducted at six sites in 1961, eight sites in 1962-1963, and ten sites since 1964. Site locations are in the trawl data-package (http://hdl.handle.net/1813/11217) and only catches at standard sites are used here. For each survey, one haul was conducted during the day at each standard site (locations presented in the trawl locations table, http://hdl.handle.net/1813/11217), ranging from 5 to 12 m in depth. The ten standard sites are indicated in the trawl location table. Surveys were conducted in mid summer through the fall in all years, and in the spring in some years. Surveys were initiated around mid July and continued at 1 week intervals until 3 surveys were completed in October. Age-0 estimates are calculated from average catch per ha swept in trawls between July 15 and Aug 15 for Aug 1, Aug 16 to Sep 15 for Sep 1, and September 16 to October 23 for October 1 values. Spring surveys were conducted on 2-3 dates, centered on May 1, and were completed in 1965-67, 1969-71, 1981, 1983-2008. Age-1 estimates for May 1 are from spring trawls in end of April – early May. Trawl data for all species and specifically for all walleye age groups are in the trawl data package. Average lengths is calculated from lengths in trawl samples for trawls done in the 7 days before and after Aug 1, Sep 1, Oct 1 and May 1. If fewer than 10 age 0 walleye were caught during these 14 days, we included fish caught in 14 days before and after this date but only if fish were available both prior and after the 1st of the month.

section.title: Gill net surveys
section.para: Standard gill net surveys have been conducted each year on Oneida Lake, NY since 1957, except for 1974. In each year except 1957, multifilament gillnets were used to sample fifteen standardized sites in an established sequence from the first Monday in June through mid-September. In 1957, all sites were sampled, but not in the established sequence. Sample locations are given in http://hdl.handle.net/1813/11216. At each site, two nets (91.2 m x 1.83 m) were set on the bottom of the lake and allowed to fish overnight for approximately 12 hours. Each net consisted of two gangs of six 7.6-m panels with mesh size (as stretch mesh) that ranged from 38 mm to 102 mm at 12.7-mm increments (1.5” to 4”). Nets were hung on a ½ basis, seamed to #120 top and bottom lines using #9 spun nylon twine at 20 cm intervals.

section.title: Mark-recapture estimates
section.para: Mark-recapture estimates for walleye have been conducted on Oneida Lake occasionally (since 1957, 24 years for walleyes). Since 1995, biannual mark-recapture estimates for walleyes have been conducted, including 2007. Between 15,000 and 25,000 walleye are caught in trap net at the Constantia Fish Cultural Station or Shackelton Point and given year specific fin clips. Scale samples are collected from a subsample of marked fish for age estimation. Recapture efforts included all standard sampling gear (gill nets and 5.5 m trawls), electrofishing, and 12.2 m trawls. Electrofishing is conducted beginning in late September and continued through October. The shoreline is divided into 8 areas of approximately equal length and sampled at night (until a minimum of 5 h on time was spent in each area) with a boom type electrofishing boat equipped with Smith-Root Type VI-A electronics. A 12.2 m trawl was fished in 4 areas of the lake (4 h in each area) beginning in early September and continuing through October. Effort is similar in all areas to minimize bias caused by non-random mixing of marked and unmarked fish. Mark-recapture estimates were calculated separately for each age group or group of ages. The equation used to calculate the walleye population in both groups is Chapman’s modification of the Petersen index with replacement: N = {(M+1)*(C+1)/(R+1)}-1, where N is the population of fish in April, M is the total number of fish marked in April, C is the total number of fish captured during the year, and R is the total number of fish marked in April that were recaptured during the year.

section.title: Estimation of walleye abundance
section.para: Thus, three methods to estimate adult walleye abundance are available in the Oneida Lake data set: standard gill net sets, bottom trawls, and mark-recapture estimates. Irwin et al. (2008) combined these estimates in an estimation model using AD Model Builder© software (Otter Research Ltd). The estimation of parameters was driven by a nonlinear estimation procedure, which arrived at a set of parameter values that minimized a concentrated form of the negative log likelihood by simultaneously minimizing the differences between the observed and predicted values for gillnet catches, the trawl CPUE, and the adult mark-recapture population estimates (the objective function). Parameters estimated included age-specific catchabilities in the two gears, a fishing mortality and a mortality associated with cormorant predation. The estimates are constrained such that the abundance of a year class declines with age – an assumption that holds as long as immigration is limited. The output includes estimates of the walleye population in each age class from age 1 to age 7+. Although AD Model Builder© allows for simultaneous estimation of a large number of parameters, the model can get over-parameterized. To avoid this problem, Irwin et al. (2008) fixed natural mortality rates at 0.10 (instantaneous rates), and calculated fishing and cormorant mortality rates as a constant rate applied to the proportion of each age class that was vulnerable. For fishing mortality, this was estimated as the proportion larger than the size limit; for mortality due to cormorants, this was the proportion smaller than 15 inches.

The abundance data in the table Adult walleye in Oneida Lake is calculated as follows. We consider the Irwin et al. (2008) estimates of age-specific catchability in the gill nets and trawls to be the best possible given the data (see the catchability data table). We also consider the Irwin et al. (2008) population estimates to be the best available for time periods when mark-recapture estimates were not conducted at least each second year. These periods are 1978-1987 and 1992-1994 in the current data set. For time periods with mark recapture estimates, we consider those to be the best possible estimator of walleye abundance age 4 and older. Thus, our best estimator is calculated as follows: 1) Equal to the mark-recapture estimates when available for age 4 and older. 2). When mark-recapture estimates are available for the previous and following year, the estimate is based on the surrounding years assuming the same mortality rates in both years. 3) Mark-recapture years are not available for two time periods, 1992 – 1994 and 1978-1987. For these time periods, the estimate is taken directly from Irwin et al. (2008). 4) For sub-adult walleye (age 1-3) we use the average of trawl and gill net catches corrected for the age-specific catchabilities of Irwin et al. (2008). Data for age-0 walleye were published in Hall and Rudstam (1999), and for all walleye age groups in Irwin et al. (2008). Length at age is average back-calculated length at age and therefore represent spring lengths prior to the sampling season. They are calculated from all back calculated lengths obtained for that year class. Thus, length at age 1 for the 2002 year class are based on age 1 caught in 2003, age 2 caught in 2004,, age 3 caught in 2005 etc. These lengths are the averages of males and females. For more information, see Irwin et al. (2008).

dataTable.entityDescription: Catchability related to walleye density in fish/ha for different age groups in standard gill nets and 5.5-m bottom trawls. To obtain walleye density in fish/ha, divide catch (in #/ha swept for trawl and total catch in 15 standard sets for gill net) by catchability. Trawl and gill net catches by age are published in eCommons and KNB (Rudstam and Jackson 2008). Length at age is average back calculated length at age and therefore represent spring lengths prior to the sampling season. Minimum and maximum length at age represent the range of mean values obtained for different year classes.
